Add GET /api/share route support for optional ?cursor=. Query shares with WHERE user_id = currentUser AND expires_at > now(), ordered by created_at DESC, limited to 50 plus cursor pagination logic. Return { items, nextCursor } where each item contains only { id, bucket, key, expiresAt, ttlSeconds, createdAt } and explicitly never includes the URL. Define and document the cursor format, likely based on created_at and id for stable ordering, and ensure expired rows are filtered out before pagination is applied.
<info added on 2026-05-22T03:37:35.233Z>
Implement GET /api/share in app/api/share/route.ts with optional cursor query parsing and explicit projection-only response. Use plaintext cursor format `<createdAt_ms>_<id>` and cap schemas.ts cursor length at 256. Parse by splitting on `_`; since ULID uses Crockford base32 and never contains `_`, decoding is unambiguous and log/debug friendly. If cursor decode fails, throw `new z.ZodError([{ code: "custom", message: "malformed cursor", path: ["cursor"] }])` so withApi returns the standard 400 validation.invalid flattened payload.

Query active shares for the current user only, excluding expired rows before pagination, ordered newest-first by `created_at DESC, id DESC`. Implement cursor pagination with drizzle WHERE logic: `or(lt(createdAt, cursor.ts), and(eq(createdAt, cursor.ts), lt(id, cursor.id)))` to fetch rows strictly after the cursor in descending order. Do not rely on ULID monotonicity alone; use timestamp + id lexical tie-break for deterministic paging.

Use peek+1 pagination: select `LIMIT 51`, return the first 50 as `items`, and derive `hasMore` / `nextCursor` from the 51st row instead of issuing a separate COUNT(*). `nextCursor` should be built from the last returned item’s createdAt/id when more rows exist; otherwise return null.

GET should have no rate limit and no audit logging, consistent with other read-heavy list endpoints. Ensure the response item type/ShareSummary excludes any URL-bearing fields: only `{ id, bucket, key, expiresAt, ttlSeconds, createdAt }`, and explicitly do not select `url` or `url_hash`, keeping the SQL projection as a strict whitelist to prevent accidental leakage.

Test coverage:
- newest-first ordering by createdAt DESC then id DESC;
- rows with `expires_at <= now` are filtered out;
- rows from other users are filtered out;
- 52-row pagination: page1 returns 50 + nextCursor, page2 returns 2 + nextCursor=null, combined unique ids == 52;
- malformed cursor returns 400;
- unauthenticated request returns 401.
</info added on 2026-05-22T03:37:35.233Z>

