<info added on 2026-05-22T11:45:04.817Z>
Deliberate deviation from Task 24 implementation detail #3: R2 unit tests do not use aws-sdk-client-mock. The project standard is to intercept S3Client.send() with vi.fn(), as documented in tests/unit/r2/control.test.ts (header comment) and tests/unit/r2/presign.test.ts.

Reason: this keeps the real @aws-sdk/client-s3 Command classes in play so their serialize step still runs during tests. That means field-name mistakes such as Bucket vs bucket or PartNumber vs partNumber fail at test time instead of being masked. This is especially valuable for the R2 S3-compatible surface, where incorrect AWS input keys are a common failure mode. aws-sdk-client-mock matches at the Command layer and would hide that class of bug.

Locked test pattern:
const send = vi.fn().mockResolvedValueOnce({ Buckets: [...] });
const s3 = { send } as unknown as S3Client;
await listBuckets(s3);
expect(send.mock.calls[0][0]).toBeInstanceOf(ListBucketsCommand);
expect(send.mock.calls[0][0].input).toEqual({});

Do not refactor existing R2 tests to aws-sdk-client-mock unless a follow-up preserves real Command-class construction and assertions.
</info added on 2026-05-22T11:45:04.817Z>
